nd its popularity exploded in the early 19th century, largely as a result of the fame of  Arthur Wellesley  (  1769–1852 ), Duke of Wellington, the victor at the Battle of Waterloo and subsequently prime minister. Further influences were  Tennyson's  Idylls of the King (  1859–85 ), and the widespread Victorian interest, especially among the Pre-Raphaelites, in things medieval in general and in Arthurian legend in particular."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705183,"age":1,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705184,"age":11,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705185,"age":21,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Arthur de Chevauchesul was born in 1085, in Tatworth, Somerset, England. He married Matilda d'Oiley about 1115, in Tetsworth, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1120, in Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 35."},"et":{"1085–1120":"1085–1120","1089–1141":"1089–1141","1116–1145":"1116–1145","1106":"1106","1116":"1116","1145":"1145","1089":"1089","about 1115":"umbe